To customize a `TextBox` control to display a date in the format of "MM/YYYY" in WPF C#, you can set the `Text` property of the `TextBox` control to a formatted string. Here's an example:

```C#
DateTime date = DateTime.Now;
textBox.Text = date.ToString("MM/yyyy");
```

In the above code, `textBox` is the name of the `TextBox` control to be customized. The `ToString` method is used to format the date string. The `"MM/yyyy"` is the format specifier for the month and year components of the date.

You can also use the `DateTime.TryParseExact` method to parse a string with a specific format into a `DateTime` object and then format it. This approach can be used when you want to set the text of a `TextBox` control from a `DateTime` object that's retrieved from a database or some other source.

Here's an example:

```C#
string dateString = "06/2021";
DateTime date;
if (DateTime.TryParseExact(dateString, "MM/yyyy", CultureInfo.InvariantCulture, DateTimeStyles.None, out date))
{
    textBox.Text = date.ToString("MM/yyyy");
}
```

In the above code:

- `dateString` is the string to be converted to a `DateTime` object.
- `"MM/yyyy"` is the format specifier for the month and year components of the date.
- `CultureInfo.InvariantCulture` specifies the format provider.
- `DateTimeStyles.None` specifies that no additional styles should be applied.
- `textBox` is the name of the `TextBox` control to be customized.

To format the text of a `TextBlock` in a `MM/YYYY` format after the user enters a date, you can handle the `LostFocus` event of the `TextBlock`. Here's an example:

```xml
<TextBlock x:Name="DataOrigem" Text="{Binding MyDate, Mode=TwoWay}" LostFocus="DataOrigem_LostFocus"/>
```

In the above code, `DataOrigem` is the name of the `TextBlock` control that displays the date and `MyDate` is the property in your view model that holds the date value entered by the user.

In the `DataOrigem_LostFocus` event handler method, you can parse the text of the `TextBlock` control to a `DateTime` object and then format it in the `MM/YYYY` format using the `ToString` method. Here's an example:

```csharp
private void DataOrigem_LostFocus(object sender, RoutedEventArgs e)
{
    if (DateTime.TryParseExact(DataOrigem.Text, "MM/yyyy", CultureInfo.InvariantCulture, DateTimeStyles.None, out DateTime date))
    {
        DataOrigem.Text = date.ToString("MM/yyyy");
    }
}
```

In the above code, `DataOrigem` is the name of the `TextBlock` control and `MyDate` is the property in your view model that holds the date value entered by the user. The `TryParseExact` method is used to parse the text of the `TextBlock` control to a `DateTime` object with the `"MM/yyyy"` format. If the parse operation is successful, the `ToString` method is used to format the date value in the `MM/YYYY` format and set the formatted string as the `Text` property of the `TextBlock` control.

Note that in order to bind to the `MyDate` property, you need to set the `DataContext` of the `UserControl` or `TextBlock`. You can achieve this by setting the `DataContext` of your `UserControl` to your view model instance, either in XAML or code-behind.
